AllLife Bank: Customer Segmentation¶

Background & Context¶

AllLife Bank wants to focus on its credit card customer base in the next financial year. They have been advised by their marketing research team that the penetration in the market can be improved. Based on this input, the Marketing team proposes to run personalized campaigns to target new customers as well as upsell to existing customers. Another insight from the market research was that the customers perceive the support services of the bank poorly. Based on this, the Operations team wants to upgrade the service delivery model, to ensure that customer's queries are resolved faster. Head of Marketing and Head of Delivery both decide to reach out to the Data Science team for help.

Objective¶

The objective of our analysis is to identify different segments in the existing customer based on their spending patterns as well as past interaction with the bank.

# While doing uni-variate analysis of numerical variables we want to study their central tendency and dispersion.
# Let us write a function that will help us create boxplots and histograms for any input numerical variables.
# This function takes the numerical column as the input and returns the boxplots and histograms for the variable.
# This will also help us write faster and cleaner code.
def histogram_boxplot(data, xlabel = None, title = None, font_scale=1, figsize=(15,7), bins = None):
    """ Boxplot and histogram combined
    data: 1-d data array
    xlabel: xlabel 
    title: title
    font_scale: the scale of the font (default 2)
    figsize: size of fig (default (9,8))
    bins: number of bins (default None / auto)

    
    """
    mean = np.mean(data)

    sns.set(font_scale=font_scale) # setting the font scale of the seaborn
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(2, sharex=True, gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (.25, .75)}, figsize=figsize) # creating the 2 subplot
    sns.boxplot(data, ax=ax_box2,showmeans=True,color="steelblue") # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.distplot(data,kde=False, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins,palette="winter") if bins else sns.distplot(data,kde=False, ax=ax_hist2,color="black") # histogram will be made
    ax_hist2.axvline(mean, color='g', linestyle='--') # mean will shown as vertical line in the histogram
    if xlabel: ax_hist2.set(xlabel=xlabel) # xlabel
    if title: ax_box2.set(title=title) # title of the graph
    plt.show() # for plotting the graph

Observations & Insights:¶

Cluster 0:

  • These customers have an average credit limit around the average credit limit of the sample, which is at about 35k.
  • These customers have a few more credit cards than average (avg in this sample is 5).
  • Customers of this cluster prefer to visit the bank in person as opposed to calling or visiting the website. This is noted by the fact that the individuals tend to visit the bank more than average and call and visit the website less than average.

Cluster 1:

  • Customers of Cluster 1 have lower credit limits than the average.
  • 50% of these customers only have 2 credit cards, which is notably lower than the average of 5 cards.
  • 75% of these customers only visit the bank twice, with 50% only visiting once.
  • If these customers are seeking assistance, they opt to make phone calls. This is noted by the fact that they make more calls to the bank than the other 2 clusters by far.
  • Even though these customers will visit online slightly more than average, they will still much prefer to make a phone call to seek assistance.

Cluster 2:

  • Cluster 2 is the high profile customer.
  • These customers have incredibly high credit limits and a large amount of credit cards, much higher than the average in both categories.
  • These customers are highly independent. They prefer to visit online for all of their banking needs, visiting online far, FAR more frequently than the other clusters.
  • These individuals visit the bank and make phone calls to the bank FAR less frequently than the other two clusters. As noted earlier, these customers are highly independent.

Hierarchical Clustering¶

In [51]:
# cophenet index is a measure of the correlation between the distance of points in feature space and distance on dendrogram
# closer it is to 1, the better is the clustering
distance_metrics = [ 'Euclidean','Chebyshev','Mahalanobis','Cityblock']
linkage_methods = ['Single', 'Complete', 'Average', 'Weighted']
high_cophenet_corr = 0
high_dm_lm = [0,0]
for dm in distance_metrics:
    for lm in linkage_methods:
        Z = linkage(subset_scaled_df, metric=dm)
        c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z , pdist(subset_scaled_df))
        print('Cophenetic correlation for distance metrics {} and linkage method {} is {}'.format(dm,lm,c))
        if high_cophenet_corr < c:
            high_cophenet_corr = c
            high_dm_lm[0] = dm
            high_dm_lm[1] = lm

linkage_methods = ['single', 'complete', 'average','median','ward', 'weighted']

high_dm_lm = [0,0]

for lm in linkage_methods:
    Z = linkage(subset_scaled_df, metric='euclidean', method=lm)
    c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z , pdist(subset_scaled_df))
    print('Cophenetic correlation for distance metrics {} and linkage method {} is {}'.format('euclidean',lm,c))
    if high_cophenet_corr < c:
        high_cophenet_corr = c
        high_dm_lm[0] = dm
        high_dm_lm[1] = lm
print('*'*110)

In [54]:
# List of all linkage methods to check
methods = ['single',
           'average', 
           'complete',
           'centroid',
           'ward',
          'weighted']

# Calculate the pairwise distance form the dataset to be used in the cophenetic correlation calculation
#pw_distance = pdist(credit_scaled)

# Create lists to save results of coph calculation
compare_cols = ['Linkage', 'Cophenetic Coefficient']
compare = []

# Create a subplot image
fig, axs = plt.subplots(len(methods), 1, figsize=(15, 30))

# Enumerate through the list of all methods above
# Get linkage, plot dendrogram, calculate cophenetic coefficient
for i, method in enumerate(methods):
    
    Z = linkage(subset_scaled_df, metric='euclidean', method=method)

    dendrogram(Z, ax=axs[i]);
    axs[i].set_title(f'Dendrogram ({method.capitalize()} Linkage)')
    coph_corr, coph_dist = cophenet(Z, pdist(subset_scaled_df))
    axs[i].annotate(f'Cophenetic\nCoefficient\n{coph_corr:0.2f}', 
                    (0.80, 0.80),
                    xycoords='axes fraction')
    compare.append([method, coph_corr])

Observations:¶

  • It seems ward linkage has the clearest and most distinct clusters.
  • Following this, it seems that complete linkage has the next most distinct clusters.

Observations & Insights:¶

First and foremost, I will first state that the clusters formed by both K-Means and Hierarchical Clustering are EXTREMELY similar, if not identical. I think our ability to form these exact 3 distinct clusters by 2 separate methods is a sign that these 3 clusters are real and clear enough that we can explore our demographic further by making notes of these individuals who fall into these clusters. With this being said, I will continue with the insights and observations.

Cluster 0:

  • These customers have an average credit limit around the average credit limit of the sample. 75% of individuals in this cluster have an average credit limit of 50k or lower.
  • These customers have only slightly more credit cards than average.
  • Customers of this cluster greatly prefer to visit the bank in person as opposed to calling or visiting the website. This is noted by the fact that the individuals tend to visit the bank more than average and call and visit the website less than the other two clusters, except for Cluster 2, who call even less frequently than Cluster 0.

Cluster 1:

  • Customers of Cluster 1 have by FAR much lower credit limits than the average, being almost an entire standard deviation lower.
  • 50% of these customers only have 2 credit cards, which is notably lower than the average of 5 cards. Also when looking at this particular trait, these individuals are even greater than 1 whole standard deviation below the mean.
  • 75% of these customers only visit the bank twice, with 50% only visiting once.
  • If these customers are seeking assistance, they opt to make phone calls. This is noted by the fact that they make more calls to the bank than the other 2 clusters by far.
  • Even though these customers will visit online slightly more than average, they will still much prefer to make a phone call to seek assistance.

Cluster 2:

  • Cluster 2 is the high profile customer.
  • These customers have incredibly high credit limits and a large amount of credit cards, much higher than the average in both categories.
  • These customers are highly independent. They prefer to visit online for all of their banking needs, visiting online far, FAR more frequently than the other clusters.
  • These individuals visit the bank and make phone calls to the bank FAR less frequently than the other two clusters, making even fewer phone calls than Cluster 0. As noted earlier, these customers are highly independent.

Conclusions & Business Recommendations:¶

Conclusions:¶

As a researcher, I believe one of the best feelings is being able to replicate results. What does a result mean if only able to be achieved once? The fact that we were able to get the same 3 distinct clusters through 2 different methods (K-Means Clustering and Hierarchical Clustering) is amazing to me. I believe that in this dataset, we've truly done good work and were able to find clusters that could further help us in marketing and demographic exploration in order to learn more about what kinds of individuals make up these 3 clusters.

Business Recommendations:¶

  • Cluster 0 seems to be the idea of the truly "average" customer. Though not literal in terms of statistical analysis, I believe the Cluster 0 customer is a "sweet spot" customer. These customers don't require too much assistance and they are not too complicated with their desires. They seek help quickly and in-person at the bank. I believe that these customers don't like to complicate things by attempting to figure things out online by themselves or over the phone. They are simple, average, and the most easygoing customer. I believe that in the future, when marketing a new product, these customers should be the target demographic as they are truly the "average" in terms of the AllLife Bank customer.
  • Cluster 1 customers need more help. Perhaps they're new to banking? Perhaps they are young? We can do demographic exploration to gain more insight on this cluster, however these are individuals with low credit limits and not many cards. As previously stated, this could be because they're young or new to banking or even perhaps because they need financial assistance. These individuals need help when it comes to banking. They come to the bank less frequently than Cluster 0 without a doubt, however they make far more calls than either of 2 clusters. In the future, when attempting to market to this demographic, I recommend perhaps an "accessible" product with a lot of forgiveness. For example, when introducing banking products to this cluster, I would recommend a simple product with no annual fees or low interest rates. I believe after these customers become accustomed to AllLife Bank and our products, they can grow to become Cluster 0 or even Cluster 2.
  • Cluster 2, I believe, is by far the most distinct cluster. These customers are independent and affluent. These are individuals with a lot of experience with banking and do not require much assistance as they opt to figure things out themselves online. They make very few visits to the bank and with even fewer phone calls ever made than either of the 2 clusters. In the future, when marketing to this cluster, I believe that this is the ideal cluster to offer premium banking products and services. I would perhaps suggest a credit with high interest rates but with high credit limits and zero foreign transaction fees. These individuals are the least of the AllLife Bank's worries from my perspective. I believe that customers who fall into Cluster 2 are high value customers. These customers are the money-makers for AllLife Bank and we should look to retain them to the best of our ability.
